**SOLUTION**
Using the approximation from PS6 we obtain

$${f(x_{k+1}) + f(x_k)\over 2} = { u'(x_{k+1}) + u'(x_k) \over 2} + {a(u(x_{k+1}) +  u(x_k)) \over 2}â‰ˆ {(u_{k+1} - u_k ) \over h} + {a u_{k+1}\over 2} + {a u_k \over 2}$$

So we get

$$\left(\frac{a}{2}-\frac{1}{h}\right)u_k + \left(\frac{a}{2}+\frac{1}{h}\right)u_{k+1} = \frac{f(x_{k+1})+f(x_k)}{2}$$

We want to prove that $\sup_{k=1,...,n-1}|u(x_k) - u_{k}|$ converges to 0 as $n\to \infty$.

Take $\hat u = [u_0,...,u_{n-1}]^T$ and rewrite the system as

$$\hat L \hat u = \begin{bmatrix} c_0 \\ \hat fá¶  \end{bmatrix}$$

where $f_k = {f(x_{k})+f(x_{k-1}) \over 2}$, $k=1,...,n-1$ and 

$$\hat L =  
\begin{bmatrix} 
1 \\
{a\over 2} - {1 \over h} & {a\over 2} + {1 \over h} \\
& {a\over 2} - {1 \over h} & {a\over 2} + {1 \over h}\\
&& \ddots & \ddots \\
&&& {a\over 2} - {1 \over h} & {a\over 2} + {1 \over h}
\end{bmatrix}$$

Note that $\hat L$ is lower bidiagonal.

Now, similarly to Euler's methods convergence theorem, we study consistency and stability.

##### Consistency:
Our discretisation approximates the true equation.

$$
\begin{aligned}
LÌ‚ u &= \begin{bmatrix} c_0 \\
{u(x_1) - u(x_0) \over h} + {a\over2}(u(x_1) + u(x_0)) \\
â‹® \\
{u(x_{n-1}) - u(x_{n-2}) \over h}  + {a\over2}(u(x_{n-1}) + u(x_{n-2}))\end{bmatrix}
= \begin{bmatrix} c_0 \\
\frac{1}{2}\left({u(x_1) - u(x_0) \over h} +{u(x_1) - u(x_0) \over h} + {a}(u(x_1) + u(x_0))\right) \\
â‹® \\
\frac{1}{2}\left({u(x_{n-1}) - u(x_{n-2}) \over h} + {u(x_1) - u(x_0) \over h} + {a}(u(x_{n-1}) + u(x_{n-2}))\right)\end{bmatrix} \\
&= \begin{bmatrix} c_0 \\
\frac{1}{2}\left(u'(x_0) + a u(x_0) + u''(Ï„_0) h + u'(x_1) + a u(x_1) + u''(Ïƒ_1) h \right)\\
â‹® \\
\frac{1}{2}\left(u'(x_{n-2}) + a u(x_{n-2}) + u''(Ï„_{n-2}) h + u'(x_{n-1}) + a u(x_{n-1}) + u''(Ïƒ_{n-1}) h \right) \end{bmatrix} = 
\begin{bmatrix} c_0 \\
{f(x_0)+f(x_1)\over 2} + {u''(Ï„_0)+u''(Ïƒ_1)\over 2} h \\
â‹® \\
{f(x_{n-2})+f(x_{n-1})\over 2} + {u''(Ï„_{n-2})+u''(Ïƒ_{n-1})\over 2} h \end{bmatrix} \\
&= 
\begin{bmatrix} c_0 \\ \hat fá¶  \end{bmatrix} + \begin{bmatrix} 0 \\ Î´ \end{bmatrix}
\end{aligned}
$$

where $x_k â‰¤ Ï„_k, Ïƒ_k â‰¤ x_{k+1}$, and uniform boundedness implies that $\|Î´\|_âˆ = O(h)$

##### Stability:
The inverse does not blow up the error.

$$
\hat L = \underbrace{\begin{bmatrix} 1 \\ & \left({a\over 2} + {1 \over h}\right) \\ && â‹± \\ &&& \left({a\over 2} + {1 \over h}\right)  \end{bmatrix}}_D 
\underbrace{\begin{bmatrix} 1 \\ \left({a\over 2} + {1 \over h}\right)^{-1}\left({a\over 2} - {1 \over h}\right)  & 1 \\ & â‹± & â‹± \\ && \left({a\over 2} + {1 \over h}\right)^{-1}\left({a\over 2} - {1 \over h}\right) &1 \end{bmatrix}}_{ L}
$$

Thus, we have 
$$
\| L^{-1}\|_{1 â†’ âˆ} â‰¤ \left|
 \left({a\over 2} + {1 \over h}\right)^{-1}\left({a\over 2} - {1 \over h}\right)
\right|^{n-1} = O(1)
$$
as $n â†’ âˆ$, where one can take logarithms and use L'Hopitals rule to show that it actually tends to a limit.
Note that 
$$
\left|{a\over 2} + {1 \over h}\right|^{-1} = \left|{h \over {ah \over 2} + 1}\right|\le 2h
$$
for sufficiently small $h$ (or large $n$).
Combining stability and consistency we have, for sufficently small $h$,
$$
\|ğ®á¶  - ğ®\|_âˆ  = \|\hat L^{-1} (\hat Lğ®á¶  - \hat Lğ®)\|_âˆ  = \| L^{-1} D^{-1} \begin{bmatrix} 0 \\ Î´ \end{bmatrix} \|_âˆ â‰¤ 2h \| L^{-1}\|_{1 â†’ âˆ} \|Î´\|_1 = O(h).
$$

